The Chronicle Nqobile Tshili, Chronicle Reporter THE Zimbabwe National Water Authority (Zinwa) board led by Engineer Bongile Ndiweni on Tuesday visited the Gwayi-Shangani dam site to assess progress made following the resumption of construction works last month. <img class="alignnone wp-image-551021 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/06/Zinwa-check-1.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/06/Zinwa-check-1.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/06/Zinwa-check-1-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> The construction works at Gwayi-Shangani dam resumed last month after Chinese engineers contracted to the project returned to the country a year after being held in the Asian nation due to Covid-19 travel restrictions. The construction of the dam is expected to be completed by year end. <img class="alignnone wp-image-551022 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/06/Zinwa-check-3.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/06/Zinwa-check-3.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/06/Zinwa-check-3-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> The Gwayi-Shangani dam construction is part of the National Matabeleland Zambezi Water Project which upon completion is expected to provide a permanent water solution for Bulawayo and Matabeleland region. It is also expected to create an irrigation greenbelt for communities in Matabeleland North. <img class="alignnone wp-image-551023 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/06/Zinwa-check-4.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/06/Zinwa-check-4.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/06/Zinwa-check-4-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Government has already embarked on a 260km Gwayi-Shangani Dam-Bulawayo pipeline which is expected to be completed by end of next year. The Gwayi-Shangani Dam construction and completion have been made a top priority and this year with Government allocating $4,5 billion towards the project. <img class="alignnone wp-image-551024 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/06/Zinwa-check-5.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/06/Zinwa-check-5.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/06/Zinwa-check-5-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> The Zinwa board is today holding high level meetings with the management at the parastatal following Tuesdayâ€™s dam tour.